1
00:00:00,976 --> 00:00:09,067
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

2
00:00:10,951 --> 00:00:19,163
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

3
00:00:21,385 --> 00:00:29,818
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

4
00:00:31,942 --> 00:00:36,746
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

5
00:00:39,628 --> 00:00:41,990
So now we've managed to get through the fourth day.

6
00:00:42,631 --> 00:00:44,232
The first three days were bad.

7
00:00:44,713 --> 00:00:46,594
Blood, sweat and tears.

8
00:00:47,856 --> 00:00:49,878
If you think about it, how else could it have been?

9
00:00:49,898 --> 00:00:54,503
In one wild axe we cut through old habits and established new ones.

10
00:00:55,543 --> 00:00:57,244
That's always got to be painful in itself.

11
00:00:58,026 --> 00:01:00,328
Never mind the difficulty of the posture and so on.

12
00:01:01,607 --> 00:01:06,695
It's a bit like finding yourself in the army, or worse, a prison, subjected to a new regime.

13
00:01:06,756 --> 00:01:08,959
Here, of course, willingly so.

14
00:01:11,123 --> 00:01:13,707
We all of us have particular, perhaps peculiar habits.

15
00:01:14,328 --> 00:01:20,379
We get up at a certain time, sleep for a certain amount, have breakfast at this time, not that, and so on.

16
00:01:21,359 --> 00:01:27,430
And what we find is that if our habits are disturbed in any way, there's always the pain of dislocation.

17
00:01:28,608 --> 00:01:30,230
If there's a good reason, we don't mind.

18
00:01:30,831 --> 00:01:33,415
We take it with good heart.

19
00:01:33,435 --> 00:01:38,262
But if there's no reason, or rather we don't see a good reason, we get irritable and bolshie.

20
00:01:40,305 --> 00:01:44,411
When we come into spiritual training, we always find there's a routine to get used to.

21
00:01:45,772 --> 00:01:48,177
And for the most part, it's always training with other people.

22
00:01:49,638 --> 00:01:52,823
It's difficult also because we're stuck in our ways.

23
00:01:53,784 --> 00:01:56,269
To change our habits is to loosen us up a bit.

24
00:01:57,480 --> 00:02:01,665
So these past three days have been a sort of spiritual boot camp.

25
00:02:01,686 --> 00:02:11,419
From now on, I hope, you begin to feel a relaxation, an ease with the rhythm of the course, and a lessening of gross physical pain caused by the posture.

26
00:02:13,020 --> 00:02:20,991
But more, I hope that you've accommodated psychologically, and no longer find yourself struggling with, or at worst against, the schedule.

27
00:02:22,522 --> 00:02:24,766
So now, the other great problem arises.

28
00:02:25,508 --> 00:02:29,294
Up till now, we've had to deal with pain in all its variegated form.

29
00:02:30,215 --> 00:02:35,364
From now on, I think you'll find there will arise moments of ease, even pleasure and delight.

30
00:02:36,605 --> 00:02:45,460
I'm not saying to expect it, but it may just come up, and here we can fall into the grave error of negligence and indulgence.

31
00:02:47,026 --> 00:03:04,631
Remember, the purpose of vipassana on a psychological level is to take the suffering out of pain and the indulgence out of pleasure and see if there is a relationship with the world beyond all that which is actually more satisfying indeed, rewarding.

32
00:03:06,052 --> 00:03:16,948
We need then to understand the pleasure syndrome and to be convinced intellectually that happiness, true contentment is not to be found there indeed, cannot be found there

33
00:03:17,991 --> 00:03:24,661
Nibbana has to be something other than sensual, mental or emotional worlds that can be so enjoyable.

34
00:03:26,683 --> 00:03:37,397
This brings us to the psychological paradigm that the Buddha discovered known as Dependent Origination or perhaps better Interdependent Origination the Paticca Samuppada.

35
00:03:38,800 --> 00:03:45,348
Some of you will have seen the representation of this in the Tibetan picture called The Wheel of Dependent Origination.

36
00:03:46,375 --> 00:03:57,056
Here, I shall only be concerned with the part that relates specifically to the problem of indulgence and suffering, and I shall indicate the Pali terms for those who are familiar with this teaching.

37
00:03:57,717 --> 00:04:02,426
The Buddha begins by pointing out that at root the problem is one of ignorance.

38
00:04:03,352 --> 00:04:10,079
It is from this position of not knowing that we presume to know, and our presumptions become our delusions.

39
00:04:10,919 --> 00:04:19,588
And it is according to our deluded understanding that we live out our lives, causing distressful, occasionally anguished cycles of behaviour.

40
00:04:21,290 --> 00:04:24,353
The first thing about pleasure is that it brings delight.

41
00:04:25,293 --> 00:04:28,617
An obvious statement, no doubt, but herein lies the whole problem.

42
00:04:29,473 --> 00:04:30,334
Now take toast.

43
00:04:31,196 --> 00:04:33,778
I've yet to meet someone who doesn't like toast.

44
00:04:34,478 --> 00:04:37,120
Some like it hot, some cold, some soggy.

45
00:04:37,841 --> 00:04:40,124
Some with marmalade, others with honey.

46
00:04:40,964 --> 00:04:42,185
Most with anything.

47
00:04:42,846 --> 00:04:48,110
But up until now, I'm of the opinion that all human beings love toast.

48
00:04:49,653 --> 00:04:58,401
When delicious toast falls upon the tongue, all that happens is certain chemical and electrical signals are passed on into the brain.

49
00:04:58,550 --> 00:05:00,951
and the first percepts are simple and basic.

50
00:05:02,494 --> 00:05:09,540
At this level, known as contact, passa, the mind perceives only hot and cold, sweet and sour, and so on.

51
00:05:10,781 --> 00:05:25,637
It's not until there's been a moment of digestion in the mind itself that definitions such as toast arise, and with them all the memories of scrumptious times and warm kitchens going back all the way to childhood.

52
00:05:26,882 --> 00:05:30,208
the great British breakfast.

53
00:05:30,228 --> 00:05:36,257
All these connections go to build up, around that initial taste, a glorious euphoria.

54
00:05:36,999 --> 00:05:45,110
This is the level of feeling, vedana, and it includes other mental attributes, such as perception and memory.

55
00:05:46,322 --> 00:05:50,548
Once this glorious state has arisen, there comes the desire to get into it.

56
00:05:51,290 --> 00:05:53,132
Now that's the greed, that's the tanha.

57
00:05:53,814 --> 00:05:56,197
But what is this tanha, this greed, this craving?

58
00:05:56,898 --> 00:05:58,821
It is just that wanting to indulge.

59
00:05:59,581 --> 00:06:03,026
The judgmental mind arises, this is good, this is wonderful.

60
00:06:03,487 --> 00:06:09,035
How amazing that a simple piece of toast can create such a glorious interior environment.

61
00:06:09,295 --> 00:06:10,115
I'm so happy.

62
00:06:10,156 --> 00:06:11,959
This is the life.

63
00:06:13,406 --> 00:06:18,192
Now I hope that during meal times you're getting into contact very clearly with this mental state.

64
00:06:19,093 --> 00:06:30,507
Hold for a while a tantalizing morsel just in front of your mouth and really experience that craving, that wanting to snap at it and gobble it all up.

65
00:06:30,526 --> 00:06:38,435
As soon as tanha has arisen, as soon as the craving for a pleasure has arisen, the next moment is one of identification.

66
00:06:38,668 --> 00:06:39,851
I am this desire.

67
00:06:40,312 --> 00:06:41,314
I am this delight.

68
00:06:41,795 --> 00:06:42,959
There's no objectivity.

69
00:06:43,399 --> 00:06:47,290
There's no separation between the enjoying and the enjoyer.

70
00:06:47,850 --> 00:06:48,872
They become unified.

71
00:06:49,454 --> 00:06:51,259
I, me, want toast.

72
00:06:52,100 --> 00:06:55,428
Now this is called Upadana Grasping.

73
00:06:56,658 --> 00:07:24,622
follows is the action bhava a gluttonous dance the actual indulgence and that's the moment when this whole process has been empowered by will chaitanya and in so doing karma is created and the habit is reinforced the habit not just of indulging in toast if that isn't bad enough but of the whole deluded understanding that happiness true contentment is to be found in sensual pleasure

74
00:07:26,509 --> 00:07:38,363
So let's review these kernel links on the wheel of dependent origination where the Buddha points out we continue to reinforce our delusions and so cause ourselves continuous suffering.

75
00:07:40,507 --> 00:07:42,988
First there is the initial contact with the object.

76
00:07:44,110 --> 00:07:52,821
Here, although we're just talking about the sense of taste it doesn't simply refer to the five senses but to the internal senses of the mind.

77
00:07:53,797 --> 00:07:57,944
It's the same syndrome when we're indulging in fantasies or daydreaming.

78
00:07:59,204 --> 00:08:06,497
This initial contact refers simply to the primary stimuli that come into consciousness, that we become aware of.

79
00:08:07,918 --> 00:08:17,374
As for the sense of taste, the five flavours as enumerated by the Chinese tradition seem to be apt, sweet and sour, salty, bitter and astringent.

80
00:08:18,350 --> 00:08:23,889
All, or some of these, are worked into a concept in the mind and there's a recognition.

81
00:08:24,690 --> 00:08:25,072
Toast.

82
00:08:27,199 --> 00:08:30,250
Now this pasa refers only to initial contact.

83
00:08:31,225 --> 00:08:34,328
By the way, at times it is useful to know the Pali words.

84
00:08:35,149 --> 00:08:42,577
It is true of translation from any language that one cannot entirely grasp a foreign word with all its meanings and nuances in another language.

85
00:08:43,399 --> 00:08:46,842
That is why I would like to introduce you in this course to key words.

86
00:08:47,783 --> 00:08:50,346
But you don't have to learn Pali to make spiritual progress.

87
00:08:50,966 --> 00:08:54,971
Thank heavens for that, or I'd give up now myself.

88
00:08:54,951 --> 00:08:56,794
This contact is very basic.

89
00:08:57,397 --> 00:09:01,644
With the eyes, it is simply colour and shape before it takes on any meaning.

90
00:09:02,767 --> 00:09:09,619
With hearing, it is the volume, pitch, tone, quality and movement of sound before any tune or recognisable speech.

91
00:09:11,121 --> 00:09:17,955
If you think it's not possible, just repeat a word to yourself like banana and keep doing it concentrating just on the sound.

92
00:09:18,863 --> 00:09:23,741
And I think you will find that soon enough, it really does become a nonsensical sound.

93
00:09:24,485 --> 00:09:25,207
Banana.

94
00:09:26,051 --> 00:09:26,874
Banana.

95
00:09:27,758 --> 00:09:28,660
Banana.

96
00:09:29,384 --> 00:09:30,206
Banana.

97
00:09:33,038 --> 00:09:37,664
At the very base of this contact, Pasa, are the four great elements.

98
00:09:38,265 --> 00:09:53,671
Earth, the qualities of hard and soft, water, the quality of cohesiveness, elasticity, stickiness, fire, the qualities of heat and cold, and finally air, the qualities of movement and stillness.

99
00:09:55,092 --> 00:10:00,902
It would seem the ancients, including the Greeks, thought that they were the building blocks of the universe.

100
00:10:02,013 --> 00:10:06,256
from a spiritual insight point of view, whether they are or not, is not relevant.

101
00:10:07,298 --> 00:10:16,488
What we are experiencing is how we, the mind, contacts the world, and how from these initial stimuli, or impulses, we create a world.

102
00:10:17,928 --> 00:10:28,240
And remember, how we contact the world is dependent not only on the stimuli coming at us such as light, but on the receptive sense, the I.

103
00:10:29,485 --> 00:10:34,331
What a person who is colorblind sees is not the same as someone with ordinary sight.

104
00:10:35,312 --> 00:10:37,596
The world we live in is of our own making.

105
00:10:38,738 --> 00:10:47,270
We construct it from this initial contact, from stimuli, from the sense base and from a primary cognition, a recognition of it.

106
00:10:48,993 --> 00:10:58,547
Now what is important about this level of perception is that there is as yet no distortion by way of thought, past experience or emotional value.

107
00:10:59,894 --> 00:11:03,639
That's why the sensations of the breath are so important in our practice.

108
00:11:04,601 --> 00:11:10,172
They are neutral and so they don't have great historical, emotional or conceptual value.

109
00:11:11,354 --> 00:11:14,379
So we can easily see the simple qualities of movement.

110
00:11:15,520 --> 00:11:20,889
And to see movement in detail is to begin to experience radical transience.

111
00:11:21,393 --> 00:11:22,956
Radical impermanence.

112
00:11:23,940 --> 00:11:26,687
Everything really is arising and passing away.

113
00:11:26,727 --> 00:11:30,919
A sensation appears and then disappears completely.

114
00:11:30,940 --> 00:11:36,515
And to perceive transience at the profoundest level is to be liberated.

115
00:11:37,947 --> 00:11:51,116
So although we've centered on toast, and I owe it to my teacher, Sayuru Janaka, to see the process of eating as a very wonderful opportunity to experience all this, we can take this investigation into every moment of our lives.

116
00:11:52,179 --> 00:11:56,208
When hearing a bird or a car passing, or the wind in the trees,

117
00:11:56,188 --> 00:12:14,419
when looking at a flower or the landscape or the shrine, when smelling the aromas of food or of the incense, when feeling the points of contact in movement, both in formal walking meditation and simple actions such as feeling the sheets before you pull them back and rise from the bed.

118
00:12:15,682 --> 00:12:20,070
We can say that this is our work to get down to this level of perception.

119
00:12:21,366 --> 00:12:22,889
Bury yourself in the body.

120
00:12:24,210 --> 00:12:30,918
Once this level of perception is clarified, then all the steps to building a world begin to reveal themselves.

121
00:12:31,698 --> 00:12:36,085
And what is important to us is that we see clearly how we mess things up.

122
00:12:36,825 --> 00:12:38,486
Things can be so much better.

123
00:12:40,990 --> 00:12:43,153
So that is the point of contact.

124
00:12:44,475 --> 00:12:46,496
And that brings me back to the piece of toast.

125
00:12:47,977 --> 00:12:57,349
As soon as this recognition, it is toast, occurs, all our memories, conceptual and emotional, around toast, engender an emotional response.

126
00:12:58,650 --> 00:13:07,900
That interior atmosphere of pleasurable joy, an internal environment of delight, this is vedana, feeling.

127
00:13:09,003 --> 00:13:16,871
It's not that we need to remember actual memories, though I dare say, if we set to it, we could write a book, The Memoirs of a Toasterholic.

128
00:13:18,370 --> 00:13:21,355
Now Vedana refers to feeling, all feeling.

129
00:13:22,155 --> 00:13:27,423
We're lucky in English because the word feeling covers virtually all the meaning of Vedana.

130
00:13:28,765 --> 00:13:34,855
We say, I feel the wind on my cheeks, the sun on my face, and I'm not feeling well.

131
00:13:35,817 --> 00:13:39,282
All this refers to sensations in the body, physical feelings.

132
00:13:40,206 --> 00:13:46,214
But we also say, I feel sad, I feel happy, a great emotional feeling came over me.

133
00:13:46,974 --> 00:13:49,216
This obviously refers to our heart life.

134
00:13:50,958 --> 00:13:57,365
So vedana feeling refers to everything we feel, sensations, feelings, moods and emotions.

135
00:13:58,567 --> 00:14:03,312
And unsurprisingly, they can be divided into pleasant, unpleasant and neutral feelings.

136
00:14:05,384 --> 00:14:26,638
Returning again to our mystical toast, once this inner environment of pleasant feelings has arisen, then there is what might be called a movement within the mind, an attraction, a drawing towards, all of which has the flavor of wanting, desiring, craving, a desire to sink into it, to immerse.

137
00:14:27,559 --> 00:14:30,884
That's tanha, craving, the desire to indulge.

138
00:14:33,058 --> 00:14:35,121
Again, tanha is more than indulgence.

139
00:14:35,962 --> 00:14:39,748
It is how we react to what is pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

140
00:14:40,870 --> 00:14:43,874
Towards the pleasant, there is that reaction of wanting.

141
00:14:44,615 --> 00:14:46,918
Towards the unpleasant, of not wanting.

142
00:14:47,578 --> 00:14:49,782
And towards the neutral, of ignoring it.

143
00:14:51,163 --> 00:14:55,129
We ignore neutral feelings because desire seeks something stimulating.

144
00:14:57,351 --> 00:15:00,096
We need to be very alert to catch these reactions.

145
00:15:00,700 --> 00:15:02,422
then that's also very much our job.

146
00:15:03,481 --> 00:15:12,090
As we shall see later, if we can hold the process to this point, we are in the best position for a dharma insight, a spiritual insight.

147
00:15:14,091 --> 00:15:20,197
Now once this point of feeling Vedana has arisen, then there's that sudden collapse into identification.

148
00:15:21,357 --> 00:15:23,120
I, the self, want that.

149
00:15:23,379 --> 00:15:24,620
Me, I want it.

150
00:15:25,841 --> 00:15:30,066
That's the grasping link, upadana, on the wheel of dependent origination.

151
00:15:31,143 --> 00:15:33,264
This is the moment we lose objectivity.

152
00:15:34,025 --> 00:15:38,971
From now on we are ensnared in the desire, compulsive behaviors, addictions, and so on.

153
00:15:40,832 --> 00:15:42,193
It can stop what happens next.

154
00:15:43,095 --> 00:15:48,179
Once there is that identification with want, we become two-year-olds.

155
00:15:48,201 --> 00:15:50,283
The whole desire is impulsed with energy.

156
00:15:51,023 --> 00:15:54,005
And before we know it, we empower that desire.

157
00:15:54,787 --> 00:16:00,373
We make a decision, often quite unintentionally, compulsively, impulsively.

158
00:16:00,606 --> 00:16:05,812
will, cetana, arises to bring into fruition that desire of self.

159
00:16:06,854 --> 00:16:10,398
I become bhava, I become a toast eater.

160
00:16:13,442 --> 00:16:14,783
How crucial that moment is.

161
00:16:15,945 --> 00:16:26,277
Whenever we do something, create an action, be it of a thought, word or deed, we bring an idea, a desire, out of mere potential into the actual.

162
00:16:27,606 --> 00:16:31,434
This is the moment of becoming, on the dependent origination.

163
00:16:32,937 --> 00:16:35,023
This is the moment when we create karma.

164
00:16:35,845 --> 00:16:38,549
This is the moment when we exercise the power of will.

165
00:16:39,812 --> 00:16:46,307
The toast is eaten with blind gusto, eyes shut with little low guttural gruntings.

166
00:16:48,397 --> 00:17:01,291
Now surely it is obvious how the simple indulgence in a harmless piece of toast can gather such emotional commitment and physical momentum that the act turns to addiction, even to self-destruction.

167
00:17:02,591 --> 00:17:05,494
Such can be the path of a toast devotee.

168
00:17:08,258 --> 00:17:15,045
However, oh the misery of it, pleasure decreases while craving increases.

169
00:17:15,952 --> 00:17:19,981
and we find ourselves in a spiral of famished dissatisfaction.

170
00:17:21,925 --> 00:17:24,151
We have a great party of Thanksgiving to toast.

171
00:17:24,771 --> 00:17:28,359
We all agree to have another, but it never lives up to the promise.

172
00:17:29,842 --> 00:17:45,650
There's always that desire for one more, but that second piece never lives up to the promise of the first, especially as we come close to the end of our proper physical appetite, and we begin to feel we've overeaten with all the unpleasant feelings that arise.

173
00:17:46,912 --> 00:17:49,757
Our greed is always greater than our need.

174
00:17:52,166 --> 00:17:54,509
This is the inbuilt obsolescence of pleasure.

175
00:17:55,730 --> 00:17:59,194
Even though we adore toast, we can have too much of a good thing.

176
00:18:00,236 --> 00:18:07,765
So the saying goes, why is it that the same pleasure source can't give us the same continuous buzz?

177
00:18:07,785 --> 00:18:08,605
Take horror movies.

178
00:18:09,547 --> 00:18:11,509
Many people like the thrill of being frightened.

179
00:18:12,210 --> 00:18:13,471
Not really frightened, of course.

180
00:18:13,711 --> 00:18:14,512
Pretend fright.

181
00:18:15,623 --> 00:18:23,992
But you can see from the vast variety of horror movies how writers have to be ever more creative and horrifying to maintain the level of buzz.

182
00:18:25,493 --> 00:18:29,179
When we see those old Frankenstein movies, we can't help but chuckle.

183
00:18:29,838 --> 00:18:32,221
Poor old Frankenstein with that bolt through his neck.

184
00:18:33,683 --> 00:18:40,010
We become bored so quickly and then starts the search for variety, for distraction.

185
00:18:41,257 --> 00:18:43,182
Variety is the spice of life.

186
00:18:43,884 --> 00:18:44,646
Well, it is, isn't it?

187
00:18:45,430 --> 00:18:47,777
If life is the pursuit of happiness in pleasure.

188
00:18:49,280 --> 00:18:53,815
Until now, we've been fairly basic in our idea of pleasure.

189
00:18:53,878 --> 00:18:55,363
basic sensual pleasures.

190
00:18:56,104 --> 00:19:07,873
But this refers to all pleasure, even the most refined, artistic, aesthetic pleasures, even the most ecstatic, elevated, exalted states of spiritual bliss.

191
00:19:07,893 --> 00:19:11,382
It's all worldly pleasure, as far as the Buddha's concerned.

192
00:19:11,564 --> 00:19:26,726
And any indulgence in it will bring about that characteristic vicious cycle of delight, satisfaction, boredom, search for variety, delight, satisfaction, boredom, search for variety, and so on.

193
00:19:28,228 --> 00:19:34,196
And what we find is that the more we indulge desire, the greater the attachment, the greater the addiction.

194
00:19:36,286 --> 00:19:39,332
Herein lies another angle on our delusive states.

195
00:19:40,673 --> 00:19:44,821
It is only when our addiction is fulfilled do we feel normal.

196
00:19:45,844 --> 00:19:46,704
Let's consider that.

197
00:19:47,968 --> 00:19:49,891
Taking an obvious case of the drug addict.

198
00:19:51,213 --> 00:19:59,509
So long as there's craving, the addict feels out of balance, in a state of suffering, agitated, ready to commit crimes.

199
00:20:00,721 --> 00:20:02,849
But when they're drugged up, they feel fine.

200
00:20:03,953 --> 00:20:05,701
It wouldn't occur to them to commit a crime.

201
00:20:05,942 --> 00:20:07,288
They're happy, fulfilled.

202
00:20:08,534 --> 00:20:10,395
And that's what happens to us, isn't it?

203
00:20:11,257 --> 00:20:13,439
We open the fridge door, and there's no milk.

204
00:20:13,980 --> 00:20:14,721
No milk for tea.

205
00:20:15,682 --> 00:20:16,583
A spat of anger.

206
00:20:17,263 --> 00:20:18,625
We look around for someone to blame.

207
00:20:19,326 --> 00:20:20,166
Then the depression.

208
00:20:20,646 --> 00:20:22,970
The awful thought of having to drink tea without milk.

209
00:20:23,651 --> 00:20:24,070
No way.

210
00:20:24,751 --> 00:20:27,434
Better to suffer a dash to the shops.

211
00:20:27,454 --> 00:20:29,576
Suddenly we're rushing down the streets for a bottle of milk.

212
00:20:30,157 --> 00:20:30,498
Rushing.

213
00:20:30,858 --> 00:20:31,159
Why?

214
00:20:32,319 --> 00:20:32,621
Anger.

215
00:20:32,800 --> 00:20:33,301
Desire.

216
00:20:34,282 --> 00:20:38,186
And all to get that feeling of well-being, of happiness in pleasure.

217
00:20:38,555 --> 00:20:39,455
from a cup of tea.

218
00:20:42,038 --> 00:20:46,523
Perhaps this syndrome can more easily be seen in the way humans behave sexually.

219
00:20:47,464 --> 00:20:56,474
When sexual happiness becomes just an end in itself, then again there is this underlying belief that happiness is to be found in raw physical pleasures of sex.

220
00:20:57,796 --> 00:21:06,486
The Kama Sutra, the Indian text that goes into all sorts of erotic postures, is yet another manifestation of how the human heart spins off into addiction.

221
00:21:07,461 --> 00:21:09,403
an insatiable desire for more.

222
00:21:10,545 --> 00:21:14,008
But like anything else, the same old routines become boring.

223
00:21:14,769 --> 00:21:20,575
The Karma Sutra is an expression of a very bored and occupied ruling caste.

224
00:21:20,595 --> 00:21:26,641
When ordinary sex becomes boring, there's a search for sex with a difference, kinky sex, fetishisms.

225
00:21:27,481 --> 00:21:33,688
This soon gets boring too, and kinkiness may turn to deviation, and the fall into crime is always possible.

226
00:21:35,321 --> 00:21:42,353
It's not just compulsive tea drinkers and drug addicts and sexual obsessives, but anyone who is lost in the four great worldly pursuits.

227
00:21:43,494 --> 00:21:47,862
All the pleasures of life, fame, power and riches.

228
00:21:48,923 --> 00:21:50,205
What else does the self want?

229
00:21:51,428 --> 00:21:57,718
I wants to be famous, powerful, rich and have any pleasure it wants right there at its fingertips.

230
00:21:58,458 --> 00:22:05,046
Just think of all those people we give power to, the media barons, the multinational executives, the prime ministers.

231
00:22:06,107 --> 00:22:13,056
Just think of all those we adulate, the film stars, pop stars, sports stars, and pay out of our noses to satisfy.

232
00:22:14,357 --> 00:22:19,545
Just think of how we allow people to amass ridiculous fortunes, the Bill Gates of this world.

233
00:22:20,566 --> 00:22:23,789
Why do we, as a society, allow such grossness?

234
00:22:24,766 --> 00:22:31,954
We need only examine ourselves and see how much our own lives are driven by these same self-driven desires.

235
00:22:34,396 --> 00:22:47,031
Sometimes if we're truthful with ourselves we shall catch ourselves in some dark fantasy and then we can see how desire unchecked that has become an addiction so easily leads to crime.

236
00:22:48,493 --> 00:22:53,440
When desire is unsatisfied frustration, anger and self-righteousness arise.

237
00:22:54,517 --> 00:22:59,782
then into robbery, violence, murder, and what have you, sometimes on a massive national scale.

238
00:23:01,365 --> 00:23:11,017
It's frightening when we look back at human history to acknowledge how destructive this essential delusion has been, this delusion that we can find happiness in pleasure.

239
00:23:12,378 --> 00:23:14,662
Indeed, it leads to criminal insanity.

240
00:23:15,482 --> 00:23:21,569
What else would you call Stalin, Hitler, Pol Pot and such like, and all their myriad cronies, but criminally mad?

241
00:23:23,051 --> 00:23:26,817
So much of this terrible destruction comes about because of frustration.

242
00:23:27,679 --> 00:23:30,182
The anger we feel when we don't get what we want.

243
00:23:31,463 --> 00:23:33,467
That awful little vicious circle.

244
00:23:34,348 --> 00:23:36,711
I want, can't, will have.

245
00:23:38,193 --> 00:23:42,780
How easily a seemingly harmless desire can turn into a nasty aggression.

246
00:23:44,002 --> 00:23:46,326
Little children are wonderful at manifesting this one.

247
00:23:47,468 --> 00:23:52,434
They get angry when they can't get what they want and when they really can't get what they want, they cry.

248
00:23:54,035 --> 00:24:02,763
If the vicious circle of desire, desire frustrated and violence fails, then there's nothing for it but to spin off into depression and self-pity.

249
00:24:04,766 --> 00:24:07,067
Worse, underneath all this, is fear.

250
00:24:07,568 --> 00:24:09,210
Fear of loss, fear of change.

251
00:24:10,310 --> 00:24:15,656
The more we treasure an object, anything we become attached to, the more we fear its loss.

252
00:24:16,778 --> 00:24:17,838
Hence the locked door.

253
00:24:18,519 --> 00:24:20,801
Hence the worry that the car might be stolen.

254
00:24:21,423 --> 00:24:24,507
It's not that such fears aren't legitimate, there are thieves about.

255
00:24:25,508 --> 00:24:29,453
But even if there weren't, there'd still be the fear of the possible loss of pleasure.

256
00:24:30,674 --> 00:24:35,642
Remember here, pleasure refers to anything, anything at all, that brings us delight.

257
00:24:37,263 --> 00:24:42,431
Take hearing and all it means in terms of human communication and the joy of sound.

258
00:24:43,511 --> 00:24:45,034
What a loss that would be!

259
00:24:45,605 --> 00:24:51,299
as soon as we have an earache, especially if we haven't had one for ages, suddenly fear arises.

260
00:24:52,323 --> 00:24:54,186
Could this be serious enough to make me deaf?

261
00:24:55,369 --> 00:25:00,163
Can you imagine the feelings of Beethoven as he began to realize that his hearing was going?

262
00:25:00,845 --> 00:25:02,127
What a mortification!

263
00:25:03,002 --> 00:25:07,573
Not that he allowed such a catastrophe in any way to diminish his work.

264
00:25:07,593 --> 00:25:08,275
And that's the point.

265
00:25:08,855 --> 00:25:14,910
Those who have lost their hearing, once accommodated, find it does not undermine the quality of their lives.

266
00:25:15,230 --> 00:25:17,214
Indeed, they find other treasures.

267
00:25:18,663 --> 00:25:27,695
Now this fear of the loss of treasured things is so great that a huge industry of insurance is built up around it, costing billions of pounds, trillions.

268
00:25:28,797 --> 00:25:29,117
Why?

269
00:25:29,959 --> 00:25:36,167
Because the self needs to protect itself against loss, with all the anger, grief and despair that it brings.

270
00:25:37,589 --> 00:25:43,657
Self has created a little island unto itself and must guard its possessions against the rest of the whole universe.

271
00:25:45,223 --> 00:25:51,952
It's only when you join a large community such as a monastic sangha that you realize that it need not be like that.

272
00:25:53,253 --> 00:25:58,140
It is through shared responsibility that so much of this emotional pain can be dissolved.

273
00:25:59,642 --> 00:26:03,067
In Islam, the community is of utmost importance, the Ummah.

274
00:26:04,208 --> 00:26:12,919
Muhammad, after all, lived right there in the midst of community and taught people to help each other bear the unfortunate vicissitudes of life.

275
00:26:14,941 --> 00:26:20,049
When the Buddha established the Sangha, almost everything was to be held in community, shared.

276
00:26:21,512 --> 00:26:27,364
But it does mean that the self has to let go of this idea of mine and begin to move towards ours.

277
00:26:29,067 --> 00:26:31,471
Such behavior leads to a lessening of that self.

278
00:26:31,892 --> 00:26:36,460
And remember, the less we have of self, the greater is our true happiness.

279
00:26:37,756 --> 00:26:40,240
For it is happiness that we're searching for all the time.

280
00:26:41,141 --> 00:26:44,586
Psychologically, the whole of our life's effort is to find happiness.

281
00:26:44,986 --> 00:26:45,686
Think about it.

282
00:26:46,888 --> 00:26:50,074
Even in the most terrible circumstances, we're searching for happiness.

283
00:26:51,214 --> 00:26:52,978
The person in pain seeks relief.

284
00:26:53,778 --> 00:26:57,003
The person in prison seeks distraction, seeks release.

285
00:26:58,526 --> 00:27:03,492
Even if we were tied up to a chair, we'd spend our time trying to find the most comfortable position.

286
00:27:04,874 --> 00:27:12,942
But the whole search is a wild goose chase and we find ourselves revolving around this cycle of desire, frustration and grief.

287
00:27:14,064 --> 00:27:23,432
But worse, when it all gets too much, there's a downward spiral into despair and that ultimate dark desire to escape it all, suicide.

288
00:27:25,855 --> 00:27:30,299
I remember the story of an Australian property tycoon not many years ago now.

289
00:27:31,020 --> 00:27:34,644
The bottom fell out of the property market and he committed suicide.

290
00:27:35,721 --> 00:27:39,288
A friend who found she was going blind began to consider suicide.

291
00:27:40,150 --> 00:27:41,933
I'm sure you all have similar examples.

292
00:27:42,935 --> 00:27:45,580
Perhaps you yourself have suffered such situations.

293
00:27:47,565 --> 00:27:50,269
So the question is, is there a way out of all this?

294
00:27:50,951 --> 00:27:51,992
Is there something better?

295
00:27:53,134 --> 00:27:54,838
Well, that's the message of the Buddha.

296
00:27:54,858 --> 00:27:56,582
That's his good news.

297
00:27:56,848 --> 00:28:07,186
There is a way of relating to the world, to the world of pleasure, in a way that doesn't bring suffering, and the kernel of that understanding lies in that area of indulgence.

298
00:28:09,250 --> 00:28:15,059
During this time on retreat we have an excellent opportunity to see how this whole syndrome works.

299
00:28:15,682 --> 00:28:27,993
how it is that indulging in pleasure brings dissatisfaction, and how it could be that without indulgence, pleasure can be enjoyed, can be appreciated, can be experienced simply as delightful.

300
00:28:29,875 --> 00:28:33,538
We can't live in this world as human beings without experiencing pleasure.

301
00:28:34,058 --> 00:28:35,279
Pleasures are a given.

302
00:28:35,881 --> 00:28:37,241
It's our natural heritage.

303
00:28:38,303 --> 00:28:44,388
It is simply how we experience some of the contact we have with our environment and our inner selves.

304
00:28:45,347 --> 00:28:49,132
So the teachings of the Buddha has nothing to do with getting rid of pleasure.

305
00:28:50,913 --> 00:28:56,619
He himself talks in this way to Ananda, his cousin, and a close companion for the last 20 years of his life.

306
00:28:58,060 --> 00:29:01,704
After going on alms round he would say, let's go to a beautiful shrine.

307
00:29:01,724 --> 00:29:03,026
Why?

308
00:29:03,646 --> 00:29:05,669
Why should he ask to go to a beautiful shrine?

309
00:29:06,549 --> 00:29:08,171
Why not a dung heap or a desert?

310
00:29:08,771 --> 00:29:09,833
Or just any old shrine?

311
00:29:10,753 --> 00:29:11,555
Why beautiful?

312
00:29:12,296 --> 00:29:13,616
And he even names a few.

313
00:29:15,082 --> 00:29:18,906
The Buddha obviously appreciated beauty, but did he indulge in it?

314
00:29:19,827 --> 00:29:22,152
Did he define the measure of his happiness by it?

315
00:29:24,315 --> 00:29:29,000
How can we be with pleasure in a non-indulgent way and still enjoy it?

316
00:29:30,061 --> 00:29:30,983
Wouldn't that be amazing?

317
00:29:31,604 --> 00:29:33,166
We'd have our cake and eat it.

318
00:29:34,107 --> 00:29:41,577
We'd be able to enjoy pleasure and not have to suffer any of the vicious cycles of frustration, grief, fear and so on.

319
00:29:43,027 --> 00:29:44,008
Well, we can.

320
00:29:44,667 --> 00:29:48,092
And what's more, we find we can enjoy things even more fully.

321
00:29:48,711 --> 00:29:58,020
And it's all in the magic of satipañña, a level of consciousness which directly experiences and yet is not caught up in that experience.

322
00:29:59,142 --> 00:30:04,606
That's why it's so important to discover what that level of consciousness is and how to maintain it.

323
00:30:06,587 --> 00:30:12,814
Consider, when we are governed by desire, doesn't that desire define for us what is pleasurable?

324
00:30:14,009 --> 00:30:17,154
A friend asks you to a meal and says they'll cook spaghetti.

325
00:30:18,056 --> 00:30:24,247
There in your mind right away is the thought of a plate of delicious spaghetti and perhaps all the delight of a Tuscan holiday.

326
00:30:25,068 --> 00:30:25,950
You look forward to it.

327
00:30:27,252 --> 00:30:29,958
But what's offered is a plate of Heinz 20th variety.

328
00:30:30,999 --> 00:30:31,480
On toast.

329
00:30:33,503 --> 00:30:34,905
Of course, one is polite.

330
00:30:35,607 --> 00:30:38,633
But it would be a hard task to cover one's disappointment.

331
00:30:39,405 --> 00:30:42,328
Now, actually, Heinz 20th is OK.

332
00:30:42,868 --> 00:30:46,292
I mean, it's edible, and if you're really hungry, it's more than palatable.

333
00:30:47,253 --> 00:30:54,461
But as you eat it at your friend's, there's just a mild disgust with it, and the mind's full of horror stories about additives.

334
00:30:56,122 --> 00:30:57,323
Isn't it the same with anything?

335
00:30:57,844 --> 00:31:06,071
Desire creates expectation, and that expectation cramps the real experience, blinds one to real experience.

336
00:31:07,586 --> 00:31:17,219
This judgmental mind, based on the skewed appreciation of what self likes and does not like, divides the whole of experience into black and white.

337
00:31:18,681 --> 00:31:20,763
I saw a tree expert on TV once.

338
00:31:21,265 --> 00:31:23,067
He was full of the glories of trees.

339
00:31:23,827 --> 00:31:28,192
Then he came upon a copper beach, and this disgust started pouring out of him.

340
00:31:28,493 --> 00:31:32,278
Words like disgusting, filthy, ugly started to come up.

341
00:31:33,359 --> 00:31:35,603
How can you be passionately hateful of a tree?

342
00:31:37,455 --> 00:31:52,990
To get out of this pleasure-indulgence syndrome we need to exercise precise awareness and on a course of this nature we can begin to see clearly how the self traps itself if we watch carefully what happens whenever pleasure arises.

343
00:31:55,092 --> 00:32:06,061
To distinguish between the pleasurable feelings and the desire for them to really catch that moment to feel the desire to indulge to really feel it

344
00:32:06,817 --> 00:32:08,378
and then to wait till it passes.

345
00:32:09,240 --> 00:32:11,061
And when it's passed, to taste the food.

346
00:32:12,242 --> 00:32:17,307
What is the experience of tasting food without previous expectation, without craving?

347
00:32:18,087 --> 00:32:22,532
To taste food just as it is, not as we would like it to be.

348
00:32:23,993 --> 00:32:30,559
What sort of mental state arises when we are experiencing something delightful and not indulging in it?

349
00:32:31,580 --> 00:32:33,923
And how do we experience that state?

350
00:32:34,105 --> 00:32:39,614
Is there identification with it, or is it like being with someone or another person who is happy?

351
00:32:41,557 --> 00:32:55,578
The difference between someone who identifies with pleasure and someone who is with their experience of pleasure, as with a good friend, is aptly put by a tale told of my favourite author, Samuel Beckett.

352
00:32:55,598 --> 00:32:59,724
Some of you may know his work, perhaps the most famous, Waiting for Godot.

353
00:33:00,817 --> 00:33:07,987
His work could be described as one long meditation on decay and death, but always with a wonderful, ironic humour.

354
00:33:09,868 --> 00:33:13,954
He was out walking with a friend in some beautiful countryside in France where he lived.

355
00:33:15,215 --> 00:33:18,660
His friend was overwhelmed and exclaimed, Oh, what beauty!

356
00:33:19,381 --> 00:33:21,804
and then asked, Doesn't it make you want to live?

357
00:33:23,145 --> 00:33:27,872
And Beckett, after a characteristic pause, replied, Well, I wouldn't want to go that far.

358
00:33:30,366 --> 00:33:33,410
Now, as always, there are two processes we need to go through.

359
00:33:34,290 --> 00:33:39,616
The seeing is Samaditti on the Eightfold Path, its correct view, right understanding.

360
00:33:40,278 --> 00:33:45,103
Listening to this talk, I hope you are at least partly intellectually convinced by the arguments.

361
00:33:46,104 --> 00:33:48,547
Later, your own thoughts about this matter may arise.

362
00:33:49,347 --> 00:33:50,969
But please, don't make an effort to think.

363
00:33:51,789 --> 00:33:53,471
That you can do after the course.

364
00:33:54,413 --> 00:34:00,580
But as you sit in meditation, you can begin to experience at first hand these physical and mental events.

365
00:34:01,682 --> 00:34:04,685
And then we realize that we can't do anything about it.

366
00:34:05,906 --> 00:34:07,990
To push them away would be to suppress them.

367
00:34:09,672 --> 00:34:15,840
So the second process is to leave the emotions of craving alone and let them arise and pass away.

368
00:34:16,641 --> 00:34:18,463
This is the level of psychotherapy.

369
00:34:19,675 --> 00:34:25,088
If the first process of understanding and seeing is psychoanalysis, the second is psychotherapy.

370
00:34:25,570 --> 00:34:26,371
Both are needed.

371
00:34:27,454 --> 00:34:33,228
The one to clarify our understanding, and the second to allow the heart to heal itself.

372
00:34:35,182 --> 00:34:50,780
And it is in suffering, in bearing gladly these emotions, desire, grasping, frustration, grief, fear, that we come to realize directly for ourselves how much suffering we cause ourselves through acts of indulgence.

373
00:34:52,503 --> 00:34:58,170
This is the spiritual insight, the dharma insight, into the characteristic of suffering, dukkha.

374
00:34:58,960 --> 00:35:11,574
And it's only when we suffer the consequences of our delusions and when we really see how suffering arises and passes away that we find the resolution to overcome the habitual temptations of our cravings.

375
00:35:12,695 --> 00:35:20,065
That's the reason spiritually for bearing with the mental distress, for developing the virtue of forbearance, of endurance.

376
00:35:21,565 --> 00:35:27,313
This is to allow the suffering to express itself and to remain fully conscious of it.

377
00:35:27,748 --> 00:35:38,547
it chisels into the understanding the consequences of unskillful behavior, so that the fear, the dread of those consequences, outbalance the strength of any craving.

378
00:35:39,990 --> 00:35:45,460
There was a friend's father who said he couldn't give up smoking, that is, until he had a heart attack.

379
00:35:48,144 --> 00:35:49,588
Let's pause here for a moment.

380
00:35:50,648 --> 00:36:06,545
So, we've looked at the process whereby we create conditionings around pleasure, the role of contact, feeling, desire and craving, grasping and identifying, and finally the act, the becoming, the creation of karma of our conditioning.

381
00:36:08,126 --> 00:36:19,237
Now, in our meditation, we can direct our attention at the mental, emotional and physical processes within us to realize all this for ourselves.

382
00:36:19,824 --> 00:36:22,871
be careful not to get caught up in thinking about it.

383
00:36:23,753 --> 00:36:26,318
It will take us away from the direct experience.

384
00:36:27,561 --> 00:36:33,934
The purpose of this talk is to convince you intellectually enough so that you really want to investigate this matter for yourself.

385
00:36:35,197 --> 00:36:39,927
I hope it's left you with a burning desire to maintain that moment-to-moment mindfulness.

386
00:36:40,969 --> 00:36:43,735
Yes, not all desire is self-based and deluded.

387
00:36:44,657 --> 00:36:51,231
Desires also arise out of our fundamental nature, the desire for true happiness and freedom from suffering.

388
00:36:52,293 --> 00:36:57,443
That sort of desire leads us to the end of wrong desires, so we should follow it.

389
00:36:59,465 --> 00:37:03,831
When we finally reach the end of suffering, then there will be no need for such desires.

390
00:37:04,552 --> 00:37:11,260
Indeed, it is the very absence of sense desire, wrong desire, that the Buddha calls Nibbāna.

391
00:37:13,704 --> 00:37:25,219
In the Dhammapada, the Buddha says, Whoever gives up desire for sense pleasures, whoever renounces worldly ambitions, whoever abandons seeking comfort in the world,

392
00:37:25,789 --> 00:37:30,034
they destroy that desire for happiness, incensual pleasure and becoming.

393
00:37:31,195 --> 00:37:34,619
Such a one is a brahmana, a fully liberated being.

394
00:37:37,021 --> 00:37:52,860
I pray your incisive perceptions into the horrors of indulgence may cut asunder the delusions of craving, and that you may achieve the great liberation from all suffering, sooner rather than later.
